Janahmadi","target":"Author/Mahyar Janahmadi","line":67},{"title":"Author/Mahyar Janahmadi","target":"Author/Mahyar Janahmadi","line":68},{"title":"PDF","target":"biblib/kaffashian_profound_2011/kaffashian_profound_2011.pdf","line":70}],"metadata":{"id":"kaffashian_profound_2011","type":"article-journal","title":"Profound alterations in the intrinsic excitability of cerebellar Purkinje neurons following neurotoxin 3-acetylpyridine (3-AP)-induced ataxia in rat: new insights into the role of small conductance K+ channels.","issued":{"date-parts":[[2011]]},"DOI":"10.33549/physiolres.932032","container-title":"Physiological Research","abstract":"Summary Alterations in the intrinsic properties of Purkinje cells (PCs) may contribute to the abnormal motor performance observed in ataxic rats. To investigate whether such changes in the intrinsic neuronal excitability could be attributed to the role of Ca 2+ -activated K + channels (KCa), whole cell current clamp recordings were made from PCs in cerebellar slices of control and ataxic rats. 3-AP induced profound alterations in the intrinsic properties of PCs, as evidenced by a significant increase in both the membrane input resistance and the initial discharge frequency, along with the disruption of the firing regularity. In control PCs, the blockade of small conductance KCa channels by UCL1684 resulted in a significant increase in the membrane input resistance, action potential (AP) half-width, time to peak of the AP and initial discharge frequency. SK channel blockade also significantly decreased the neuronal discharge regularity, the peak amplitude of the AP, the amplitude of the afterhyperpolarization and the spike frequency adaptation ratio. In contrast, in ataxic rats, both the firing regularity and the initial firing frequency were significantly increased by the blockade of SK channels. In conclusion, ataxia may arise from alterations in the functional contribution of SK channels, to the intrinsic properties of PCs.","tags":["#literature_note"],"author":[{"family":"Kaffashian","given":"Mohammad Reza","literal":""},{"family":"Kaffashian","given":"M.","literal":""},{"family":"Shabani","given":"Mohammad","literal":""},{"family":"Shabani","given":"Mohammad","literal":""},{"family":"Goudarzi","given":"Iran","literal":""},{"family":"Goudarzi","given":"Iran","literal":""},{"family":"Behzadi","given":"Gila","literal":""},{"family":"Behzadi","given":"Gila","literal":""},{"family":"Zali","given":"A.","literal":""},{"family":"A","given":"Zali","literal":""},{"family":"Janahmadi","given":"Mahyar","literal":""},{"family":"Janahmadi","given":"Mahyar","literal":""}],"citation-key":"kaffashian_profound_2011","year":"2011","dateCreated":"2026-03-31","reading-status":"to-read","aliases":["Profound alterations in the intrinsic excitability of cerebellar Purkinje neurons following neurotoxin 3-acetylpyridine (3-AP)-induced ataxia in rat: new insights into the role of small conductance K+ channels."],"author-links":["[[Author/Mohammad Reza Kaffashian]]","[[Author/M. Kaffashian]]","[[Author/Mohammad Shabani]]","[[Author/Mohammad Shabani]]","[[Author/Iran Goudarzi]]","[[Author/Iran Goudarzi]]","[[Author/Gila Behzadi]]","[[Author/Gila Behzadi]]","[[Author/A. Zali]]","[[Author/Zali A]]","[[Author/Mahyar Janahmadi]]","[[Author/Mahyar Janahmadi]]"],"attachment":["[[biblib/kaffashian_profound_2011/kaffashian_profound_2011.pdf|PDF]]"],"related":[[]]},"task_lines":[],"tasks":{},"codeblock_ranges":[],"last_embed":{"hash":"l4s604","at":1774951890598}},"smart_blocks:Research/@kaffashian_profound_2011.md#---frontmatter---": {"path":null,"embeddings":{"TaylorAI/bge-micro-v2":{"vec":[-0.01108725,-0.00196547,0.05824759,-0.03666605,-0.05340623,0.05867382,0.04365283,0.04931091,0.01298101,-0.01271738,-0.00666534,-0.08355471,0.02765503,0.03176538,0.05652147,0.05365301,-0.02550901,-0.00449604,-0.04293236,0.02846245,0.00181741,-0.0836605,0.03609735,0.02621621,-0.02323527,-0.04881253,0.03913308,0.00643923,-0.09193965,-0.28